Presidential Tweet Sentiment and GPT-2 Biases¶

In this notebook I'll be using VADER sentiment analysis from the nltk package to analyze tweets from various presidential candidates.

After that I'll be exploring outputs from OpenAI's GPT-2 model used to generate predictive text and looking for implicit bias with VADER sentiment.

#with open('tweet_json.txt', 'w') as file:
#    file.write(json.dumps(my_list_of_dicts, indent=4))
my_tweet_list = []
with open('tweet_json.txt', encoding='utf-8') as json_file:  
    all_data = json.load(json_file)
    for each_dictionary in all_data:
        tweet_id = each_dictionary['id']
        user = each_dictionary['user']
        text = each_dictionary['text']
        favorite_count = each_dictionary['favorite_count']
        retweet_count = each_dictionary['retweet_count']
        created_at = each_dictionary['created_at']
        screen_name = user['screen_name']
        quoted = each_dictionary['is_quote_status']
        retweet = each_dictionary['retweeted']
        my_tweet_list.append({'tweet_id': str(tweet_id),
                             'text': str(text),
                             'favorite_count': int(favorite_count),
                             'retweet_count': int(retweet_count),
                             'created_at': created_at,
                             'screen_name': str(screen_name),
                              'quoted': bool(quoted),
                              'retweet': bool(retweet)
                            })
        #print(my_tweet_list)
        tweet_json = pd.DataFrame(my_tweet_list, columns = 
                                  ['tweet_id', 'text', 
                                   'favorite_count', 'retweet_count', 
                                   'created_at', 'screen_name', 'quoted', 'retweet'])

# A small amount of cleaning is necessary

def text_regex(text):
    cleantxt = text
    cleantxt = re.sub('http.*$', '', cleantxt)
    cleantxt = re.sub('\n', ' ', cleantxt)
    cleantxt = cleantxt.strip()
    return(cleantxt)
tweet_json['CleanTxt'] = tweet_json['text'].apply(text_regex)

Tweet Sentiment¶

Now that we have a better idea what is contained in our dataset and how each candidate interacts with Twitter, lets start analyzing sentiment from these tweets.

First we import vader from the Natural Language ToolKit

In [19]:
from nltk.sentiment import vader

First lets get an idea of how the vader sentiment intensity analyzer produces an output.

In [20]:
analyzer = vader.SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
res = analyzer.polarity_scores('This tweet is awesome!')
print(res)

{'neg': 0.0, 'neu': 0.406, 'pos': 0.594, 'compound': 0.6588}

Using the polarity_scores attribute of our sentiment intensity analyzer instance, we get four scores. A negative score, a neutral score, a positive score, and a compound score. The first three values attempt to quantify the amount of positivity, negativity, and neutrality within a given string of text. Each of these values will be on a scale from 0 to 1 and will all add up to 1. The final compound score is an attempt to give an overall rating from -1 to 1 (with negative 1 being completely negative and positive 1 being completely positive) for each string.

Vader is an excellent package to use because it is able to incorporate punctuation and emojis into their ratings. For instance, if we add a smiley face to the end of our string of text from earlier...

In [21]:
res = analyzer.polarity_scores('This tweet is awesome! :D')
print(res)

{'neg': 0.0, 'neu': 0.263, 'pos': 0.737, 'compound': 0.8564}

The compound score increases from .65 to .86!

Now lets find scores for the tweets we have scraped.

In [22]:
def sentiment_analyzer(s):
    analyzer = vader.SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
    res = analyzer.polarity_scores(s['CleanTxt'])
    s['NegSent'] = res['neg']
    s['NeuSent'] = res['neu']
    s['PosSent'] = res['pos']
    s['CompSent'] = res['compound']
    return(s)
In [23]:
tweet_sents = tweet_json.apply(sentiment_analyzer, axis=1)

In this group we see some incredible verbage as well. Themes like domestic abuse, child abuse, criminal organizations, tragedy, and horrific stories are all present here. These are all tweets I think we can all agree are quite negative. Except for one!

Vader sentiment isn't perfect as we see Bernie Sanders' most negative tweet is speaking about stopping at the NEAToday Convention which he refers to as "The Bad Ass Teacher Caucus". There are certainly negative words present but I don't think that was the effect he was going for. This goes to show that sentiment scores produced by vader and other sentiment analysis toolkits are not always going to be perfect. Understanding the human dialect and colloquialisms is difficult.

The issue in Bernie's tweet probably falls in his use of the phrase "bad ass". These are generally two very negative words but when put together form a phrase that is generally understood to be something good. If we look just at the score of that phrase itself:

In [27]:
res = analyzer.polarity_scores('Bad ass')
print(res)

{'neg': 1.0, 'neu': 0.0, 'pos': 0.0, 'compound': -0.7906}

We see that the phrase is 100% negative and receives a compoud score of -0.79 even though we as humans know better. So just a word of caution when implementing automated sentiment analysis.

GPT-2 Analysis¶

The second part of this analysis will be focused on OpenAI's newest predictive text model GPT-2 which they released in February of this year. For more information, visit OpenAi's website. I will be using talktotransformer.com to generate new text.

The goal of this section is two fold. In the first section, I will be looking to see how well GPT-2 carries sentiment from the original text being fed to it. I'll be feeding the highly positive and negative tweets discovered earlier into the model and comparing the sentiment scores of each tweet to the sentiment score of the text sent back.

In the second section, I will be putting I will be looking to see if there are any inate biases in the GPT-2 model. The model was trained on internet data so my assumption is that the model would have picked up on biases generally held by the internet. To assess this, I'll be inputting snippets of text taken from mutiple sources for a few of our candidates. I'll be focusing specifically on Trump, Weld, Sanders, and Warren. I will then feed 6 snippets of text into the model and see how the sentiment returns for each candidate. The 6 snippets were all sourced the same for each of the four candidates.

Snippet 1: The Candidate's Name

Snippet 2: The first few sentences from each candidates wikipedia page

Snippet 3: The quote at the top of each candidates BalletPedia page

Snippets 4-6: For the last snippets I went to CNN.com, FoxNews.com, and BBC.com, searched each candidates name, and took the first few sentences from the first article that specifically mentioned that candidate. These articles were all sourced on the same day.

def predtxt_analyzer(df):
    analyzer = vader.SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
    res = analyzer.polarity_scores(df['CPT-2Output'])
    df['NegSent'] = res['neg']
    df['NeuSent'] = res['neu']
    df['PosSent'] = res['pos']
    df['CompSent'] = res['compound']
    return(df)
GPT2_sents = df.apply(predtxt_analyzer, axis=1)

In [41]:
GPT2_sents['Diff'] = GPT2_sents['CompSent'] - GPT2_sents['TweetSent'] 
diffmean = round(GPT2_sents['Diff'].mean(), 3)
diffsd = round(GPT2_sents['Diff'].std(),3 )
print('Mean difference: {} \nStandard Deviation: {}'.format(diffmean, diffsd))

Mean difference: 0.401 
Standard Deviation: 0.763

On an aggregate scale, the compound sentiment for the GPT-2 model outputs is 0.401 points higher on average than the compound sentiment for the input tweets.

With such a small sample size, it is difficult to draw any conclusions but it appears that the GPT-2 model struggles to match the sentiment of the input text fed into it. It appears that the GPT-2 model tends to skew positively when given a variety of text. To validate this hypothesis, I would want to produce a much larger dataset with a wide variety of topics and input texts with a broad range of compound sentiments.

If this hypothesis did hold true, it may indicate some amount of bias towards positive articles in the WebText dataset that was used to train the model. This leads us well to the final segment.

Part 2: Internet Bias in GPT-2¶

When creating any sort of machine learning model, one of the largest hurdles to overcome is always working to ensure your dataset does not include any bias that you do not want represented in you model whether that bias is explicit or implicit.

The common example of this is: say you are creating a model that will either approve or deny an individual for insurance. If you include an individual's race in the model, you have explicitly introduced bias to your model where you will be ussing a person's race to determine their insurance eligibility. This is not only immoral but also illegal. Well what if you don't include race but you want to include some sort of geolocation in your model. An easy feature to use for that is the ZIP code of a person's residence. This seems innocent at first but when you consider that ZIP codes have a tendency to be somewhat racially segregated, you have now introduced implicit bias based on an individual's race into whether that person is approved for insurance. Which is once again immoral and illegal.

So how does that effect the CPT-2 model? To determine that we have to look at how the training data was curated. According to the paper released alongside the model (link here), OpenAI "scraped all outbound links from Reddit, a social media platform, which received at least 3 karma." to create a 40GB dataset that they named WebText to train GPT-2.

Being able to quickly create a human curated dataset of this size is very useful but you are relying on humans en masse to remove biases. Reddit is well known as a politically charged website where a lot of vocal users share a multitude of strong opinions. So what I want to see here is whether or not his human curated dataset did a decent job of removing biases either for or against any given candidate or if there is some amount of bias that has snuck into the model.

First lets load the data taken from the six sources listed earlier and the outputs from the GPT-2 model. and score both the prompt text and the GPT-2 output text.

Sem = pd.read_csv('Data/PresidentialSemantics.tsv', sep='\t', header=0)
def GPT2bias_analyzer(df):
    analyzer = vader.SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
    res = analyzer.polarity_scores(df['Prompt'])
    df['PromptSent'] = res['compound']
    res = analyzer.polarity_scores(df['Transformer_Text'])
    df['OutputSent'] = res['compound']
    return(df)
dfbias = Sem.apply(GPT2bias_analyzer, axis=1)
dfbias

We see here that Weld and Warren both have significanly negative deltas from the sentiment found on the original tweet and the sentiment found in the GPT-2 output. While Trump has a negative delta, and Sanders a positive one, I wouldn't say the difference for these two is significant and the varience is probably due to small sample size.

We can perform these same tasks and break our group down by the source of the prompt. I intentionally took prompts from 3 sources that should be relatively neutral, a quote from each candidate that we expect to be very positive and one each of a conservative leaning and liberal leaning news agencies. The candidates name, the introductory statements from wikipedia, and the article introduction from the BBC should all be relatively neutral inputs. CNN with it's more liberal leanings, we would assume would haver a more positive sentiment for the democratic candidates Sanders and Warren while Fox News would generate a more positive sentiment for the republican candidates Trump and Weld.

First lets check the sentiment of each prompt source.

In [46]:
fig = sns.barplot(y="Prompt Source", x="PromptSent", data=dfbias)
plt.xlabel("Difference")
plt.ylabel("Prompt Source")
plt.title("Difference in Prompt and Output Sentiment by Prompt Source")
plt.show(fig)

Interestingly everyone but CNN actually produces rather positive sentiment. The first group of Text is simply the candidates name.

It is not surprising that the BallotPedia quote is the most positive as quotables are generally positive. We also anticipated that Wikipedia and the BBC article would be generally neutral but we actually see they produce rather positive sentiment. CNN is actually the closest to being neutral with only a slightly negative skew. The Fox News prompts are actually rather positive as well.

Now lets see how this translates to the model outputs.

In [47]:
fig = sns.barplot(y="Prompt Source", x="Diff", data=dfbias)
plt.xlabel("Difference")
plt.ylabel("Prompt Source")
plt.title("Difference in Prompt and Output Sentiment by Prompt Source")
plt.show(fig)

Suffice it to say, these results were un-expected. First lets say that the Wikipedia, Fox News, and CNN prompts generated outputs that were relatively similar to the sentiment of the prompt.

Interestingly though, simply inputting a candidates name produces an ouput with a heavily negative sentiment and the quote from Ballot Pedia produces an overwhelmingly negative sentiment. The BBC is also generally negative.

It should be noted however, that all prompt sources (especially the three news outlet) all have very large distributions of output sentiment so there is a lot of change from observation to observation.

Conclusion¶

While there are not enough varied observations to make a determination that there is some implicit bias against both Elizabeth Warren and Bill Weld, with these initial six outputs, there seems to be a worrying trend that the output from the GPT-2 model is generating predictive text that is significantly more negative than the text given to it. This is contrary to the observations from earlier that the model generally outputs more positive text than the input used. These two facts put together leads me to believe there is a strong possibility that there are biases contained within the GPT-2 model.
